05631nam a22008415i 9780774851510DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748515107 a10.59962/97807748515102doi  a(DE-B1597)662357  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aK487.R48 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a349.711 aLaw Commission of Canada, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLaw and Risk /cLaw Commission of Canada. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLegal Dimensions00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tOn Proof and Probability: Introduction to “Law and Risk” -- tUse of Risk Assessments by Canadian Judges in the Determination of Dangerous and Long-Term Offender Status, 1997–2002 -- tShifting the Burden of Proof: The Precautionary Principle and Its Potential for the “Democratization” of Risk -- tLegal Knowledges of Risks -- tEvidentiary Principles with Respect to Judicial Review of Constitutionality: A Risk Management Perspective -- tIntegrating Values in Risk Analysis of Biomedical Research: The Case for Regulatory and Law Reform -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe study and practice of risk analysis, risk management, and the communication of risk has been the subject of heated debates. This is no less so when law is added to the mix. Despite the law's constant search for certainty, the concept of risk itself is inherently uncertain. From the precautionary principle to the role of research ethics boards, risk remains a value-laden term, difficult to define and even more difficult to address. This book looks at law and risk in a variety of contexts and provides insight into how courts use and interpret risk and how the law allocates risk, as well as examining the regulation of risky activities. To demonstrate the linkages between law and risk, the essays tackle some difficult topics, including dangerous offenders, sex offender notification, drug courts, genetic research, pesticide use, child pornography, and tobacco advertising. This careful consideration of whether the law adequately and appropriately responds to risk will be of interest to students and scholars of law and the social sciences, as well as to law practitioners and lawmakers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication du risquexCanadaxCanada. 0aCommunication du risquezCanadazCanada. 0aDroitxCanada. 0aDroitzCanada. 0aÉvaluation du risquezCanada. 0aGestion du risquexCanada. 0aGestion du risquezCanada. 0aLawxCanada. 0aLawzCanada. 0aRisk assessmentxCanada. 0aRisk assessmentzCanada. 0aRisk communicationxCanada. 0aRisk communicationzCanada. 0aRisk managementxCanada. 0aRisk managementzCanada. 0aÉvaluation du risquexCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aHrudey, Steve E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeiss, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemmens, Trudo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevi, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacAlister, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Dawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinard, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScott, Dayna Nadine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValverde, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaring, Duff R., eco